{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"35c90a12-958a-48b5-a2a9-eae8e1337aaa","content":"Here's how to migrate your xUnit.net test project to Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n\n**1. Update packages** in your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<!-- Remove -->\n<PackageReference Include=\"xunit.runner.visualstudio\" Version=\"...\" />\n\n<!-- Add -->\n<PackageReference Include=\"xunit.runner.mtp\" Version=\"1.0.0\" />\n```\n\nKeep your existing `xunit` 2.9.3 package reference.\n\n**2. Enable MTP** by adding this property to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <TestingPlatformDotNetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotNetTestSupport>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**3. Run tests** with the same `dotnet test` command — MTP is now the underlying runner.\n\n**Key notes:**\n- `xunit.runner.mtp` replaces `xunit.runner.visualstudio` as the test host adapter.\n- Your test code itself doesn't change — `[Fact]`, `[Theory]`, etc. all work the same.\n- The built test project becomes a self-contained executable, so you can also run tests directly: `./YourTestProject.exe`.\n- If you use `dotnet test` and need VSTest compatibility temporarily, you can add `<TestingPlatformCommandLineArguments>--report-vstest</TestingPlatformCommandLineArguments>` for VSTest-format output.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"15cc2eaa-fcee-48e5-bd5b-94c71927dda4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to migrate their xUnit.net project from VSTest (using xunit.runner.visualstudio) to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). Let me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge of this migration.","outputTokens":413},"id":"1dd87b00-54b3-4f0a-89d6-c44f8296c4c1","timestamp":"2026-04-07T14:20:53.426Z","parentId":"3fd5a1c5-399a-4b28-89ca-b77ff92e8e5d"}
